	abstract = {The history of positron emission tomography (PET) can be traced to the early 1950s, when the medical imaging possibilities of a particular class of radioactive substances were first realized. It was recognized then that the high-energy photons produced by the annihilation of the positron-emitting isotopes could be used to describe, in three dimensions, the physiological distribution of "tagged" chemical compounds. After 2 decades of moderate technological developments by a few research centers, widespread interest and broadly based clinical research activity began in earnest following the development of sophisticated reconstruction algorithms and improvements in detector technology. By the mid-1980s, PET had become a tool for medical diagnosis and for dynamic studies of human metabolism. Table 6.1 indicates the significant advances in PET technology over the last 20 years.},
